I don't believe this!

40:34.833 --> 40:37.583
- Lee, how are you?
- I'm good.

40:37.792 --> 40:40.333
- What are you doing these days?
- Hanging in there.

40:40.542 --> 40:42.458
Still running and killing the girls?

40:42.667 --> 40:44.083
I'm long married.

40:44.333 --> 40:46.917
This is my wife, speaking
of married. Mary.

40:47.167 --> 40:49.708
- Where's your wife?
- She has shingles.

40:49.958 --> 40:51.417
Psychological.

40:51.708 --> 40:52.750
You a shrink?

40:52.958 --> 40:55.042
Not exactly, I'm
a psychoanalyst.

40:55.250 --> 40:57.625
Can you believe this guy?

40:57.875 --> 40:59.833
- Come and give me a call.
- A call?

41:00.208 --> 41:03.708
Monroe Gordon, and his
lovely wife, Dana.

41:04.083 --> 41:07.958
Monroe, whom you all remember
was in our "Guys and Dolls"...

41:08.667 --> 41:11.875
and who went on to a
successful singing career...

41:12.167 --> 41:13.042
in Broadway...

41:13.458 --> 41:14.917
in Atlantic City...

41:15.167 --> 41:18.333
Carlton's Restaurant off the
Sunrise Highway...

41:19.625 --> 41:22.042
and the Sunrise Lounge.

41:23.792 --> 41:27.833
Monroe will sing a song made
popular in our school years.

41:58.208 --> 42:00.750
<i>What happened to my classmates?
Everyone's so...</i>

42:01.667 --> 42:03.917
<i>mature-looking and fat.</i>

42:04.208 --> 42:06.208
<i>I didn't age that much.</i>

42:06.542 --> 42:08.875
<i>Unless I did and I can't see it.</i>

42:09.083 --> 42:13.042
<i>All these dentists, veterinarians
and antique dealers...</i>

42:13.833 --> 42:17.292
<i>capped teeth and bald heads,
grey hairs coming...</i>

42:17.833 --> 42:19.458
<i>Sam Jablon has that rug on.</i>

42:19.708 --> 42:23.375
<i>Looks like it fell on him from
a window and nobody told him.</i>

42:23.958 --> 42:27.750
<i>Some dead already. Annette
DeAngelo, breasts I caressed...</i>

42:28.000 --> 42:30.417
<i>lying cold in the ground!</i>

42:31.167 --> 42:33.833
<i>God, how I wanted to
sleep with Polly Weiss.</i>

42:34.083 --> 42:35.917
<i>Now she's turned into her mother.</i>

42:36.333 --> 42:40.333
<i>Freddie Kaplan's my age. Looks
like he's from my father's club.</i>

42:40.833 --> 42:42.833
<i>I'm fucking Prufrock.</i>

42:43.708 --> 42:47.000
I've got to change
before it's too late.

42:47.458 --> 42:48.667
Pardon me?

42:49.375 --> 42:51.250
I'm not happy, Jay.

42:51.958 --> 42:54.125
Married too young.

42:54.458 --> 42:57.875
Neither of us had the
chance to live, to explore.

42:58.167 --> 43:00.625
These aren't
my office hours.

43:00.875 --> 43:04.417
I'm talking to you while
there's still time.

43:05.042 --> 43:08.583
I just turned 40. I don't
want to look up at 50...

43:08.833 --> 43:12.167
to find I've measured out
my life with coffee spoons.

43:12.417 --> 43:14.458
Try and relax.

43:16.167 --> 43:18.417
And put the vodka down.

43:18.792 --> 43:22.458
Robin's lovely.
She's a little neurotic...

43:24.667 --> 43:28.583
but I don't want to spend my life
as husband to a schoolteacher...

43:28.958 --> 43:31.917
writing the occasional
travel piece...

43:32.250 --> 43:34.042
and never knowing...

43:34.500 --> 43:36.542
what it's like to make love...

43:36.917 --> 43:40.792
to that sleazy blonde that's
married to Monroe Gordon.

43:42.625 --> 43:43.875
The truth is that...

43:44.083 --> 43:46.667
Robin is dull in bed.

43:47.000 --> 43:49.292
Fucking Catholic
inhibitions.

43:49.542 --> 43:53.167
I don't know, maybe I
don't excite her anymore.

43:54.500 --> 43:56.958
I don't know what's true anymore.

43:57.250 --> 43:59.250
Listen, are you in treatment?

43:59.458 --> 44:01.917
One minute you're in
the school lunchroom...

44:02.167 --> 44:03.625
you fucking blink...

44:03.875 --> 44:06.500
and you're 40.
Blink again...

44:06.750 --> 44:10.625
and you can see movies at half
price for senior citizens.

44:11.708 --> 44:14.667
"Ask not for whom the bell tolls."

44:15.583 --> 44:17.500
Or to be more exact...

44:17.708 --> 44:20.333
ask not for whom
the toilet flushes.

44:34.333 --> 44:36.750
Where were you while we
were making love?

44:36.958 --> 44:40.417
You know, in high school
I was Class Writer.

44:40.625 --> 44:44.042
That's why I tell you to
forget the screenplays...

44:44.250 --> 44:47.208
- and go back to writing your novel.
- Too inhibited.

44:47.458 --> 44:49.708
So you'll never get over
some bad reviews?

44:49.917 --> 44:52.792
My two novels were
dismissed. It was brutal.

44:53.042 --> 44:55.500
Maybe after I sell a
screenplay.

44:55.750 --> 44:57.208
Film is where it's at.

44:57.417 --> 45:00.125
Who reads books anymore?
Not young kids.

45:00.333 --> 45:03.708
- They're into cinema, movies.
- I don't believe that. Nor do you.

45:03.917 --> 45:05.625
Why are you getting dressed?

45:06.167 --> 45:09.167
Going home. Isn't
that what you want?

45:10.167 --> 45:12.125
I don't know what I want.

45:12.833 --> 45:16.625
You're the only one who makes
sense to me since my divorce.

45:17.125 --> 45:19.792
I don't want someone
to make sense to.

45:20.375 --> 45:22.500
I want someone to get
irrational over me.

45:22.708 --> 45:26.750
Maybe after I sell my armoured
car robbery script...

45:26.958 --> 45:29.500
I'll get back to
something more serious.

45:29.750 --> 45:33.083
Philip's having a dinner next
week. I'd love you to come.

45:33.292 --> 45:34.833
Philip Datloff?

45:35.167 --> 45:38.500
- He's sweet. You'll like him.
- I'd be too intimidated.

45:38.958 --> 45:42.708
An editor of his stature? I'd
feel guilty I wasn't writing.

45:43.875 --> 45:47.250
- I want you two to meet.
- I won't know what to say.

45:48.417 --> 45:49.875
So what's your novel about?

45:50.083 --> 45:53.292
- I don't have a novel, it's more...
- No, he does, he does.

45:53.542 --> 45:56.333
Been working on
it for over a year.

45:56.583 --> 46:00.208
- From what I've seen, it's terrific.
- Bonnie is a gifted editor.

46:00.458 --> 46:02.500
- I know this.
- I'm grooming her for my job.

46:02.708 --> 46:04.458
I didn't have the emotional
energy to finish it.

46:04.667 --> 46:08.292
And how many people read it?
Do a film, and it reaches millions.

46:08.542 --> 46:10.958
It's not energy, it's confidence.

46:11.500 --> 46:14.500
- His first two books...
- Were obliterated. The 3 S's.

46:14.708 --> 46:17.292
Self-indulgent, sophomoric,
solipsistic.

46:17.500 --> 46:20.625
If every writer who got bad press
at first caved in...

46:20.833 --> 46:21.958
You're too thin-skinned.

46:22.167 --> 46:24.375
My God, it's V.J. Rajnipal.

46:24.750 --> 46:26.500
- Excuse me.
- Philip's his editor.

46:26.750 --> 46:30.708
What am I doing here? That guy
won the Nobel and deserved...

46:30.958 --> 46:34.792
I'm out of my league.
Awash in self-contempt.

46:35.833 --> 46:38.958
You know Irwin Shaw wrote
the best anti-war play ever...

46:39.167 --> 46:40.667
and got it all into one act?

46:40.917 --> 46:43.625
Interesting you should say
that, he was my idol.

46:43.833 --> 46:46.292
At high school I read "The
Eighty Yard Run."

46:46.500 --> 46:49.625
And I wept. Cried in class.

46:49.917 --> 46:51.792
That story made
me want to write.

46:52.000 --> 46:54.375
That and some
pieces by Saroyan.

46:54.583 --> 46:56.333
You love him too?

46:56.542 --> 46:58.792
Amazing! I love the plays
and the essays.

46:59.000 --> 47:02.875
When I think of Irwin Shaw, I
think of "Girls in Summer Dresses."

47:03.083 --> 47:05.792
The title is better than most
people's short stories.

47:06.000 --> 47:08.083
It's so elegant, economic.

47:08.375 --> 47:10.042
- It's thrilling.
- The best.

47:10.250 --> 47:12.167
Thrilling prose. Terrific.

47:13.167 --> 47:16.292
My book is about the values
of a society gone astray...

47:16.500 --> 47:18.458
a culture badly
in need of help.

47:18.667 --> 47:21.333
A country that gives a 20-year-old
kid who can barely read or write...

47:21.542 --> 47:23.958
a $100 million contract
to play basketball?

47:24.167 --> 47:27.792
And a brutal murder trial, or who
is sleeping with the President...

47:28.000 --> 47:31.042
It's all show business!
All show business!

47:31.250 --> 47:32.875
Why am I getting so shrill?

47:33.083 --> 47:35.292
I get so nervous
talking about my novel.

47:35.500 --> 47:37.125
That's why you have to finish it.

47:37.333 --> 47:39.625
- You're so encouraging.
- Screenplays have their place.

47:39.833 --> 47:41.458
But there's nothing like a
serious book.

47:41.667 --> 47:42.375
Exactly my point.

47:42.583 --> 47:44.333
In "Red Letter Day",
my first book...

47:44.542 --> 47:46.667
I touched on these themes,
but I was too green.

47:46.875 --> 47:49.208
- I remember "Red Letter Day".
- Really?

47:49.417 --> 47:51.417
Yeah, I reviewed it for
the Times.

47:51.625 --> 47:52.667
It was...

47:53.167 --> 47:54.625
extremely...

47:55.417 --> 47:57.833
half-baked,
laboured...

47:58.167 --> 47:59.333
solipsistic.

47:59.875 --> 48:02.167
There was no energy.
It was trivial.

48:02.792 --> 48:04.875
You don't mind
my being frank?

48:06.833 --> 48:08.333
Are you okay?

48:11.292 --> 48:13.417
The rest of them
will be here soon.

48:13.500 --> 48:16.917
Let's not take all day on this.
Move it along! I've got plans.

48:17.167 --> 48:20.208
- This way, Mr Adelman.
- Counselor! Nice to have you back.

48:20.417 --> 48:22.833
- It's a pleasure.
- Put him in the Green Room.

48:23.042 --> 48:26.375
You're from the ACLU, right?
Can I get you anything?

48:26.708 --> 48:29.583
Yeah. I'm expecting a call.
Can you put it through?

48:29.833 --> 48:30.917
Of course. You know each other?

48:31.125 --> 48:33.167
These gentleman are from the
South Carolina Klan.

48:33.417 --> 48:35.833
We've done a few
shows together.

48:36.083 --> 48:37.583
You're Minister Polynice!

48:37.958 --> 48:40.000
The others are in
the Green Room.

48:40.208 --> 48:42.083
